---
import '../styles/home.css';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<meta charset="utf-8" />
		<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
		<title>Yazelix - Reproducible terminal workspace</title>
		<meta
			name="description"
			content="Yazelix is a reproducible terminal workspace built around Zellij, Yazi, Helix, and a fixed runtime toolset."
		/>
	</head>
	<body>
		<div class="page-shell">
			<header class="hero">
				<nav class="nav" aria-label="Primary navigation">
					<a class="brand" href="/">
						<img src="/images/logo.png" alt="" />
						<span>Yazelix</span>
					</a>
					<div class="nav-links">
						<a href="/start/">Start</a>
						<a href="/configure/">Configure</a>
						<a href="/keybindings/">Keys</a>
						<a href="/blog/">Blog</a>
						<a href="https://github.com/luccahuguet/yazelix">GitHub</a>
					</div>
				</nav>
				<div class="hero-visual">
					<img src="/images/yazelix_current_example.png" alt="Yazelix terminal workspace screenshot" />
				</div>
				<div class="hero-content">
					<p class="eyebrow">Zellij, Yazi, Helix, terminal, config, and runtime tools in one package</p>
					<h1>Yazelix</h1>
					<p class="hero-copy">
						A reproducible terminal workspace with a managed file tree, stable editor pane, directional
						popups, a right agent sidebar, and a curated runtime that works the same locally or over SSH.
					</p>
					<div class="hero-actions">
						<a class="button primary" href="/start/">Start with Yazelix</a>
						<a class="button secondary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</header>

			<main>
				<section class="section strip">
					<div class="section-inner">
						<h2>The first successful path is short</h2>
						<p class="section-lede">
							Yazelix is package-first. Install the flake output, launch the workspace, then keep
							configuration in one JSONC file unless you intentionally choose a deeper override surface.
						</p>
						<div class="terminal" aria-label="Yazelix quickstart command">
							<div class="terminal-header">quickstart</div>
							<pre><code>nix profile add github:luccahuguet/yazelix#yazelix
yzx launch</code></pre>
						</div>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section">
					<div class="section-inner">
						<h2>Built around the daily workspace loop</h2>
						<p class="section-lede">
							The site starts with what users need on day one: launch, navigate, configure, update, and
							recover. Deeper reference docs stay available without making the first path feel like repo archaeology.
						</p>
						<div class="workflow-grid">
							<article class="panel">
								<h3>Navigate spatially</h3>
								<p>Use Alt+Shift+H/J/K/L for the left sidebar, bottom popup, top popup, and right agent sidebar.</p>
								<a href="/keybindings/">View keys</a>
							</article>
							<article class="panel">
								<h3>Edit one main config</h3>
								<p>Start with ~/.config/yazelix/settings.jsonc or open the ratconfig-backed config UI.</p>
								<a href="/configure/">Configure</a>
							</article>
							<article class="panel">
								<h3>Recover deliberately</h3>
								<p>Use doctor, reset, and ownership-aware recovery paths instead of editing generated runtime state.</p>
								<a href="/recover/">Recover</a>
							</article>
						</div>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section strip">
					<div class="section-inner">
						<h2>Product docs and project writing in one place</h2>
						<p class="section-lede">
							Docs explain the supported product. Blog posts can carry release essays, design notes, and
							lessons from the evolving terminal IDE without mixing planning state into the reference docs.
						</p>
						<div class="blog-grid">
							<article class="panel">
								<h3>Install and update</h3>
								<p>Nix profile and Home Manager paths, Cachix notes, and stale flake cache recovery.</p>
								<a href="/start/">Start guide</a>
							</article>
							<article class="panel">
								<h3>Reference docs</h3>
								<p>Runtime model, customization surfaces, keybindings, and troubleshooting checklists.</p>
								<a href="/docs/">Docs index</a>
							</article>
							<article class="panel">
								<h3>Design notes</h3>
								<p>Write about the workspace model, child repos, terminal support, and release decisions.</p>
								<a href="/blog/">Blog</a>
							</article>
						</div>
					</div>
				</section>
			</main>

			<footer class="footer">
				<div class="footer-inner">
					<span>Yazelix is built by Lucca Huguet</span>
					<a href="https://github.com/luccahuguet/yazelix">github.com/luccahuguet/yazelix</a>
				</div>
			</footer>
		</div>
	</body>
</html>
